2–1232","1070–1133":"1070–1133","1068–Female":"1068–Deceased","1110":"1110","Abt 1115":"about 1115","1152":"1152","1184":"1184","1070":"1070","Abt 1152":"about 1152","1226":"1226","1115":"1115","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1200":"1200","1133":"1133","1232":"1232","Bef. 1133":"before 1133","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Tideswell, Derbyshire, England":"Tideswell, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Musard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Durham): nickname or occupational name from Middle English <i>mustard</i> ‘mustard’ (Old French <i>mostarde</i>). The allusion could perhaps be to someone with a sharp tongue, but is probably usually to a dealer in mustard."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Musard was born about 1115, in Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Hasculf Musard, was 47 and her mother, Matilda de Richmond, was 49. She had at least 1 son with Geoffrey Foljambe Lord of Tideswell. She died in 1226, in Tideswell, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 112."},"et":{"Abt 1115–1226":"umbes 1115–1226","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1115–1226":"1115–1226","1112–1184":"1112–1184","1152–1232":"1152–1232","1070–1133":"1070–1133","1068–Female":"1068–Surnud","1110":"1110","Abt 1115":"umbes 1115","1152":"1152","1184":"1184","1070":"1070","Abt 1152":"umbes 1152","1226":"1226","1115":"1115","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1200":"1200","1133":"1133","1232":"1232","Bef. 1133":"enne 1133","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tideswell, Derbyshire, England":"Tideswell, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1115–1226":"noin 1115–1226","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1115–1226":"1115–1226","1112–1184":"1112–1184","1152–1232":"1152–1232","1070–1133":"1070–1133","1068–Female":"1068–Kuollut","1110":"1110","Abt 1115":"noin 1115","1152":"1152","1184":"1184","1070":"1070","Abt 1152":"noin 1152","1226":"1226","1115":"1115","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1200":"1200","1133":"1133","1232":"1232","Bef. 1133":"ennen vuotta 1133","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Tideswell, Derbyshire, England":"Tideswell, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1115–1226":"environ 1115–1226","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1115–1226":